<p>A <b>regular dodecahedron</b> or <b>pentagonal dodecahedron</b><sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-sathyanarayana_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-sathyanarayana-1"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dodecahedron" title=3D"Do=
decahedron">dodecahedron</a> (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Po=
lyhedron" title=3D"Polyhedron">polyhedron</a> with 12 <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Face_(geometry)" title=3D"Face (geometry)">faces</a>) c=
omposed of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polygon" title=
=3D"Regular polygon">regular</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/P=
entagonal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pentagonal">pentagonal</a> faces,=
 three meeting at each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vertex_(geo=
metry)" title=3D"Vertex (geometry)">vertex</a>. It is one of the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platonic_solid" title=3D"Platonic solid">Pla=
tonic solids</a>, described in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pla=
to" title=3D"Plato">Plato</a>'s <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pl=
atonic_dialog" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Platonic dialog">dialogues</a=
> as the shape of the universe itself. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Johannes_Kepler" title=3D"Johannes Kepler">Johannes Kepler</a> used th=
e dodecahedron in his 1596 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mysteri=
um_Cosmographicum" title=3D"Mysterium Cosmographicum">model of the Solar Sy=
stem</a>. However, the dodecahedron and other Platonic solids had already b=
een described by other philosophers since antiquity.
</p><p>The regular dodecahedron is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Truncated_trapezohedron" title=3D"Truncated trapezohedron">truncated tra=
pezohedron</a> because it is the result of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Truncation_(geometry)" title=3D"Truncation (geometry)">truncating<=
/a> axial vertices of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagonal=
_trapezohedron" title=3D"Pentagonal trapezohedron">pentagonal trapezohedron=
</a>. It is also a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldberg_polyhe=
dron" title=3D"Goldberg polyhedron">Goldberg polyhedron</a> because it is t=
he initial polyhedron to construct new polyhedra by the process of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chamfer" title=3D"Chamfer">chamfering</a>=
. It has a relation with other Platonic solids, one of them is the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron" title=3D"Regular ico=
sahedron">regular icosahedron</a> as its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Dual_polyhedron" title=3D"Dual polyhedron">dual polyhedron</a>. Othe=
r new polyhedra can be constructed by using a regular dodecahedron.
</p><p>The regular dodecahedron's metric properties and construction are as=
sociated with the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_ratio" ti=
tle=3D"Golden ratio">golden ratio</a>. The regular dodecahedron is featured=
 in some artistic and narrative works. Some toys and artifacts are also sha=
ped like regular dodecahedra, including the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Roman_dodecahedron" title=3D"Roman dodecahedron">Roman dodecahedr=
on</a>. Regular dodecahedra can also be found in nature and supramolecules,=
 as well as the shape of the universe. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Skeleton_(topology)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Skeleton (topo=
logy)">skeleton</a> of a regular dodecahedron can be represented as the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)" title=
=3D"Graph (discrete mathematics)">graph</a> called the <b>dodecahedral grap=
h</b>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Platonic_graph" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Platonic graph">Platonic graph</a>. Its property of t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamiltonian_graph" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Hamiltonian graph">Hamiltonian</a>, a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Path_(graph_theory)" title=3D"Path (graph theory)">p=
ath</a> that visits all of its vertices exactly once, can be found in a toy=
 called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosian_game" title=3D"Ico=
sian game">icosian game</a>.
</p>
