">Kepler's</a> Platonic solid model of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Solar_System" title=3D"Solar System">Solar System</a></div></div><=
/div></div></div>
<p>The regular dodecahedron is a polyhedron with twelve pentagonal faces, t=
hirty edges, and twenty vertices.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-sutton_2-0" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cit=
e_note-sutton-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> It is one of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Platonic_solid" title=3D"Platonic solid">Platonic solids</a>, a =
set of polyhedrons in which the faces are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Regular_polygons" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Regular polygons">=
regular polygons</a> that are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cong=
ruence_(geometry)" title=3D"Congruence (geometry)">congruent</a> and the sa=
me number of faces meet at a vertex.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-hs_3-0" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite=
_note-hs-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup> This set of polyhedrons is named after <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plato" title=3D"Plato">Plato</a>. In <i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theaetetus_(dialogue)" title=3D"Theaetetu=
s (dialogue)">Theaetetus</a></i>, a dialogue of Plato, Plato hypothesized t=
hat the classical elements were made of the five uniform regular solids. Pl=
ato described the regular dodecahedron, obscurely remarked, "...the god use=
d [it] for arranging the constellations on the whole heaven". <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timaeus_(dialogue)" title=3D"Timaeus (dialogue)=
">Timaeus</a>, as a personage of Plato's dialogue, associates the other fou=
r Platonic solids=E2=80=94<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_=
tetrahedron" title=3D"Regular tetrahedron">regular tetrahedron</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cube_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Cube (geometry)">cube</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Regular_octahedron" title=3D"Regular octahedron">regular octahedron</a>, an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron" title=3D"Re=
gular icosahedron">regular icosahedron</a>=E2=80=94with the four <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_element" title=3D"Classical elemen=
t">classical elements</a>, adding that there is a fifth solid pattern which=
, though commonly associated with the regular dodecahedron, is never direct=
ly mentioned as such; "this God used in the delineation of the universe."<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Aristotle" title=3D"Aristotle">Aristotle</a> also postula=
ted that the heavens were made of a fifth element, which he called <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aether_(classical_element)" title=3D"Aeth=
er (classical element)">aith=C3=AAr</a> (<i>aether</i> in Latin, <i>ether</=
i> in American English).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-wildberg_5-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-=
wildberg-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Following its attribution with nature by Plato, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johannes_Kepler" title=3D"Johannes Kepler">Johannes Ke=
pler</a> in his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harmonices_Mund=
i" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Harmonices Mundi">Harmonices Mundi</a></i=
> sketched each of the Platonic solids, one of them is a regular dodecahedr=
on.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cromwell_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-cromwell-6"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
> In his <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mysterium_Cosmographic=
um" title=3D"Mysterium Cosmographicum">Mysterium Cosmographicum</a></i>, Ke=
pler also proposed the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_Syste=
m" title=3D"Solar System">Solar System</a> by using the Platonic solids set=
ting into another one and separating them with six spheres resembling the s=
ix planets. The ordered solids started from the innermost to the outermost:=
 regular octahedron, regular icosahedron, regular dodecahedron, regular tet=
rahedron, and cube.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2003[httpsbooksgoogleco=
mbooksidbUARfgWRH14CpgPA147_147]_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2003[ht=
tpsbooksgooglecombooksidbUARfgWRH14CpgPA147_147]-7"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><span class=3D"m=
w-3d-wrapper" data-label=3D"3D"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fi=
le:Dodecahedron.stl" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uplo=
ad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Dodecahedron.stl/250px-Dodeca=
hedron.stl.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw=
-file-element" data-file-width=3D"5120" data-file-height=3D"2880"></a></spa=
n><figcaption>3D model of a regular dodecahedron</figcaption></figure>
<p>Many antiquity philosophers described the regular dodecahedron, includin=
g the rest of the Platonic solids. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Theaetetus_(mathematician)" title=3D"Theaetetus (mathematician)">Theaetetu=
s</a> gave a mathematical description of all five and may have been respons=
ible for the first known proof that no other convex regular polyhedra exist=
. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid<=
/a> completely mathematically described the Platonic solids in the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's El=
ements"><i>Elements</i></a>, the last book (Book XIII) of which is devoted =
to their properties. Propositions 13=E2=80=9317 in Book XIII describe the c=
onstruction of the tetrahedron, octahedron, cube, icosahedron, and dodecahe=
dron in that order. For each solid, Euclid finds the ratio of the diameter =
of the circumscribed sphere to the edge length. In Proposition 18 he argues=
 that there are no further convex regular polyhedra. <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Iamblichus" title=3D"Iamblichus">Iamblichus</a> states t=
hat <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippasus" title=3D"Hippasus">H=
ippasus</a>, a Pythagorean, perished in the sea, because he boasted that he=
 first divulged "the sphere with the twelve pentagons".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dod=
ecahedron#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The regular dodecahedron, as the family of Platonic solids, is a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_polyhedron" title=3D"Regular =
polyhedron">regular polyhedron</a>. It is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Isogonal_figure" title=3D"Isogonal figure">isogonal</a>, <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isohedral" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Is=
ohedral">isohedral</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isotox=
al" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Isotoxal">isotoxal</a>: any two vertices=
, two faces, and two edges of a regular dodecahedron can be transformed by =
rotations and reflections under its symmetry orbit respectively, which pres=
erves the appearance.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Relation_to_the_regular_ico=
sahedron">Relation to the regular icosahedron</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_dodecahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&am=
p;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Relation to the regular icosahedron">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:01_Dodekaeder_umschreibt_Ikosaeder.svg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/9/93/01_Dodekaeder_umschreibt_Ikosaeder.svg/330px-01_Dodekae=
der_umschreibt_Ikosaeder.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"300" height=
=3D"279" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"313" data-file-height=
=3D"291"></a><figcaption>The regular icosahedron inside the regular dodecah=
edron</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dual_polyhedron" title=3D"D=
ual polyhedron">dual polyhedron</a> of a dodecahedron is the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_icosahedron" title=3D"Regular icosahedro=
n">regular icosahedron</a>. One property of the dual polyhedron generally i=
s that the original polyhedron and its dual share the same <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Point_groups_in_three_dimensions" title=3D"Point g=
roups in three dimensions">three-dimensional symmetry group</a>. In the cas=
e of the regular dodecahedron, it has the same symmetry as the regular icos=
ahedron, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosahedral_symmetry"=
 title=3D"Icosahedral symmetry">icosahedral symmetry</a> <span class=3D"mwe=
-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inlin=
e mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.=
w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \mathrm {I} _{\mathrm {h=
} }}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">I</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
              <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">h</mi>
            </mrow>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathrm {I} _=
{\mathrm {h} }}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/a9fdfce71bda597451d015e732f835e6fc14b348" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.671ex; width:1.986ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \ma=
thrm {I} _{\mathrm {h} }}"></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-erickson_9-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedro=
n#cite_note-erickson-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The regular dodecahedron has ten three=
-fold axes passing through pairs of opposite vertices, six five-fold axes p=
assing through the opposite faces centers, and fifteen two-fold axes passin=
g through the opposite sides midpoints.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-weils_10-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedr=
on#cite_note-weils-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>When a regular dodecahedron is inscribed in a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a>, it occupies more of=
 the sphere's volume (66.49%) than an icosahedron inscribed in the same sph=
ere (60.55%).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-be_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-be-11"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> The resulting of both spheres' volumes initially began from the problem =
by ancient Greeks, determining which of two shapes has a larger volume: an =
icosahedron inscribed in a sphere, or a dodecahedron inscribed in the same =
sphere. The problem was solved by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Hero_of_Alexandria" title=3D"Hero of Alexandria">Hero of Alexandria</a>, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pappus_of_Alexandria" title=3D"Pappu=
s of Alexandria">Pappus of Alexandria</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Fibonacci" title=3D"Fibonacci">Fibonacci</a>, among others.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-herz_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-herz-12"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Apollonius_of_Perga" title=3D"Apollonius =
of Perga">Apollonius of Perga</a> discovered the curious result that the ra=
tio of volumes of these two shapes is the same as the ratio of their surfac=
e areas.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-simmons_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-simmons-13"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup> Both volumes have formulas involving the golden ratio but are taken=
 to different powers.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-sutton_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-sutto=
n-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_rectangle" title=3D"=
Golden rectangle">Golden rectangle</a> may also related to both regular ico=
sahedron and regular dodecahedron. The regular icosahedron can be construct=
ed by intersecting three golden rectangles perpendicularly, arranged in two=
-by-two orthogonal, and connecting each of the golden rectangle's vertices =
with a segment line. There are 12 regular icosahedron vertices, considered =
as the center of 12 regular dodecahedron faces.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-marar_14=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_do=
decahedron#cite_note-marar-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Relation_to_the_regular_tet=
rahedron">Relation to the regular tetrahedron</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsec=
tion"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_dodecahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&am=
p;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Relation to the regular tetrahedron">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Chiroicosahedron-in-dodecahedron.png" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/f/fa/Chiroicosahedron-in-dodecahedron.png/250px-Chiroicosahe=
dron-in-dodecahedron.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"200" height=3D"200" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1000" data-file-height=3D"1000"=
></a><figcaption>Five tetrahedra inscribed in a dodecahedron. Five opposing=
 tetrahedra (not shown) can also be inscribed.</figcaption></figure>
<p>As two opposing tetrahedra can be inscribed in a cube, and five cubes ca=
n be inscribed in a dodecahedron, ten tetrahedra in five cubes can be inscr=
ibed in a dodecahedron: two opposing sets of five, with each set covering a=
ll 20 vertices and each vertex in two tetrahedra (one from each set, but no=
t the opposing pair). As stated by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Regular_dodecahedron#CITEREFCoxeterdu_ValFlatherPetrie1938">Coxeter et al.=
 (1938)</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-coxeter-1938_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-coxeter=
-1938-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>"Just as a tetrahedron can be inscri=
bed in a cube, so a cube can be inscribed in a dodecahedron. By reciprocati=
on, this leads to an octahedron circumscribed about an icosahedron. In fact=
, each of the twelve vertices of the icosahedron divides an edge of the oct=
ahedron according to the "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Golden_s=
ection" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Golden section">golden section</a>".=
 Given the icosahedron, the circumscribed octahedron can be chosen in five =
ways, giving a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compound_of_five_oc=
tahedra" title=3D"Compound of five octahedra">compound of five octahedra</a=
>, which comes under our definition of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Stellated_icosahedron" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stellated icosah=
edron">stellated icosahedron</a>. (The reciprocal compound, of five cubes w=
hose vertices belong to a dodecahedron, is a stellated <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triacontahedron" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Triaco=
ntahedron">triacontahedron</a>.) Another stellated icosahedron can at once =
be deduced, by stellating each octahedron into a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Stella_octangula" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stella octa=
ngula">stella octangula</a>, thus forming a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Compound_of_ten_tetrahedra" title=3D"Compound of ten tetrahedra">=
compound of ten tetrahedra</a>. Further, we can choose one tetrahedron from=
 each stella octangula, so as to derive a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Compound_of_five_tetrahedra" title=3D"Compound of five tetrahedra">=
compound of five tetrahedra</a>, which still has all the rotation symmetry =
of the icosahedron (i.e. the icosahedral group), although it has lost the r=
eflections. By reflecting this figure in any plane of symmetry of the icosa=
hedron, we obtain the complementary set of five tetrahedra. These two sets =
of five tetrahedra are enantiomorphous, i.e. not directly congruent, but re=
lated like a pair of shoes. [Such] a figure which possesses no plane of sym=
metry (so that it is enantiomorphous to its mirror-image) is said to be <i>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chiral" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Chiral">chiral</a></i>."</p></blockquote>
