<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Other_related_geometric_obj=
ects">Other related geometric objects</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DRegular_dodecahedron&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Other related geometric objects"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The regular dodecahedron can be interpreted as the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goldberg_polyhedron" title=3D"Goldberg polyhedron">Gold=
berg polyhedron</a>. It is a set of polyhedra containing hexagonal and pent=
agonal faces. Other than two Platonic solids=E2=80=94tetrahedron and cube=
=E2=80=94the regular dodecahedron is the initial of the Goldberg polyhedron=
 construction, and the next polyhedron is obtained by truncating all of its=
 edges, a process called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chamfer_(=
geometry)" title=3D"Chamfer (geometry)">chamfer</a>. This process can be co=
ntinuously repeated, resulting in more new Goldberg's polyhedra. These poly=
hedra are classified as the first class of a Goldberg polyhedron.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-hart_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-hart-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
