"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_stellated_dodecahedron" title=3D"Small=
 stellated dodecahedron">Small stellated dodecahedron</a> and <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trapezohedron" title=3D"Trapezohedron">trapezoh=
edron</a></div></div></div></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stellation" title=3D"Stella=
tion">stellations</a> of the regular dodecahedron make up three of the four=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kepler%E2%80%93Poinsot_polyhedra"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Kepler=E2=80=93Poinsot polyhedra">Kepler=E2=
=80=93Poinsot polyhedra</a>. The first stellation of a regular dodecahedron=
 is constructed by attaching its layer with pentagonal pyramids, forming a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Small_stellated_dodecahedron" titl=
e=3D"Small stellated dodecahedron">small stellated dodecahedron</a>. The se=
cond stellation is by attaching the small stellated dodecahedron with <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wedge_(geometry)" title=3D"Wedge (geome=
try)">wedges</a>, forming a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_=
dodecahedron" title=3D"Great dodecahedron">great dodecahedron</a>. The thir=
d stellation is by attaching the great dodecahedron with the sharp triangul=
ar pyramids, forming a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_stell=
ated_dodecahedron" title=3D"Great stellated dodecahedron">great stellated d=
odecahedron</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTECromwell1997[httpsbooksgoogleco=
mbooksidOJowej1QWpoCpgPA265_265]_24-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTECromwell199=
7[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidOJowej1QWpoCpgPA265_265]-24"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Other related polyhedra are:
</p>
<ul><li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentagonal_trapezohedron" =
title=3D"Pentagonal trapezohedron">Pentagonal trapezohedron</a>, the commen=
cement of constructing the regular dodecahedron by truncating its two axial=
 vertices.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-montroll_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-montroll-25">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup></li>
<li>Two <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedean_solid" title=
=3D"Archimedean solid">Archimedean solids</a>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Truncated_dodecahedron" title=3D"Truncated dodecahedron">trunc=
ated dodecahedron</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Snub_dod=
ecahedron" title=3D"Snub dodecahedron">snub dodecahedron</a>. Respectively,=
 these polyhedra are obtained by truncating all vertices of a regular dodec=
ahedron and separating the pentagonal faces of a regular dodecahedron befor=
e filling the gap with equilateral triangles.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ziya_26-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodec=
ahedron#cite_note-ziya-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-kappraff_27-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahe=
dron#cite_note-kappraff-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pentakis_dodecahedron" title=
=3D"Pentakis dodecahedron">Pentakis dodecahedron</a> is the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kleetope" title=3D"Kleetope">Kleetope</a> of a re=
gular dodecahedron, obtained by affixing pentagonal pyramids to each face, =
similar to the small stellated dodecahedron, although the difference is the=
 pyramids' altitude. It is also a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Catalan_solid" title=3D"Catalan solid">Catalan solid</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-cg_28-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reg=
ular_dodecahedron#cite_note-cg-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></li>
<li>Four <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johnson_solid" title=3D"J=
ohnson solid">Johnson solids</a>=E2=80=94<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Augmented_dodecahedron" title=3D"Augmented dodecahedron">augmented d=
odecahedron</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parabiaugmented_d=
odecahedron" title=3D"Parabiaugmented dodecahedron">parabiaugmented dodecah=
edron</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metabiaugmented_dodecah=
edron" title=3D"Metabiaugmented dodecahedron">metabiaugmented dodecahedron<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triaugmented_dodecahedron" ti=
tle=3D"Triaugmented dodecahedron">triaugmented dodecahedron</a>=E2=80=94obt=
ained by attaching one, two, or three pentagonal pyramids onto the faces of=
 a regular dodecahedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-berman_29-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-b=
erman-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup></li></ul>
