mbcaption">A solved six-color sided Megaminx</div></div></div></div></div>
<p>Regular dodecahedra have been used as dice and may also have been used a=
s divinatory devices. Small hollow bronze <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Roman_dodecahedra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Roman dodecahedra=
">Roman dodecahedra</a> have been found in the northern parts of the Roman =
empire; their purpose is uncertain.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-guggenberger_30-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecah=
edron#cite_note-guggenberger-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-hill_31-0" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodeca=
hedron#cite_note-hill-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/20th-century_art" title=
=3D"20th-century art">20th-century art</a>, regular dodecahedra appear in t=
he work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M._C._Escher" title=3D"=
M. C. Escher">M. C. Escher</a>, such as his lithographs <i><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reptiles_(M._C._Escher)" title=3D"Reptiles (M. C. =
Escher)">Reptiles</a></i>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-dunlap_32-0" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note=
-dunlap-32"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salvad=
or_Dal%C3%AD" title=3D"Salvador Dal=C3=AD">Salvador Dal=C3=AD</a>'s paintin=
g <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Sacrament_of_the_Last_Sup=
per" title=3D"The Sacrament of the Last Supper">The Sacrament of the Last S=
upper</a></i> in which the room is a hollow regular dodecahedron).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELivio2003[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidbUARfgWRH14CpgPA9_=
9]_33-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regul=
ar_dodecahedron#cite_note-FOOTNOTELivio2003[httpsbooksgooglecombooksidbUARf=
gWRH14CpgPA9_9]-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ge=
rard_Caris" title=3D"Gerard Caris">Gerard Caris</a> based his entire artist=
ic oeuvre on the regular dodecahedron and the pentagon, presented as a new =
art movement coined Pentagonism.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-34=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>In modern <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Role-playing_game=
s" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Role-playing games">role-playing games</a=
>, the regular dodecahedron is often used as a twelve-sided die, one of the=
 more common <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dice#Polyhedral_dice"=
 title=3D"Dice">polyhedral dice</a>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Megaminx" title=3D"Megaminx">Megaminx</a> is a twisted puzzle simila=
r to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rubik%27s_Cube" title=3D"=
Rubik's Cube">Rubik's Cube</a> but the shape is pentagonal faces dodecahedr=
al.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-joyner_35-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-joyner-35"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the children's novel <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
The_Phantom_Tollbooth" title=3D"The Phantom Tollbooth">The Phantom Tollboot=
h</a></i>, the regular dodecahedron appears as a character in the land of M=
athematics. Each face of the regular dodecahedron describes the various <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Facial_expression" title=3D"Facial ex=
pression">facial expressions</a>, swiveling to the front as required to mat=
ch his mood.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-36" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-36"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>36<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bertrand_Russell" title=
=3D"Bertrand Russell">Bertrand Russell</a>'s 1954 short story <i>The Mathem=
atician's Nightmare: The Vision of Professor Squarepunt</i>, the number 5 s=
aid: "I am the number of fingers on a hand. I make pentagons and pentagrams=
. And but for me dodecahedra could not exist; and, as everyone knows, the u=
niverse is a dodecahedron. So, but for me, there could be no universe."<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-37" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-37"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</sp=
an>37<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
