<p>The fossil <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coccolithophore" tit=
le=3D"Coccolithophore">coccolithophore</a> <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Braarudosphaera_bigelowii" title=3D"Braarudosphaera bigelowii">=
Braarudosphaera bigelowii</a></i>, a unicellular coastal <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phytoplanktonic" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Phyt=
oplanktonic">phytoplanktonic</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
lga" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Alga">alga</a>, has a calcium carbonate=
 shell with a regular dodecahedral structure about 10 micrometers across.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-hokh_38-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-hokh-38"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>38<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The hydrocarbon <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dodecahedra=
ne" title=3D"Dodecahedrane">dodecahedrane</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Quasicrystal" title=3D"Quasicrystal">quasicrystal</a> such =
as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holmium%E2%80%93magnesium%E2%80=
%93zinc_quasicrystal" title=3D"Holmium=E2=80=93magnesium=E2=80=93zinc quasi=
crystal">holmium=E2=80=93magnesium=E2=80=93zinc quasicrystal</a> have a dod=
ecahedral shape (see figure).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-cf_39-0" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-=
cf-39"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>39<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> Some regular crystals, such as <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Garnet" title=3D"Garnet">garnet</a> and <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diamond" title=3D"Diamond">diamond</a> are also said =
to exhibit "dodecahedral" <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_=
habit" title=3D"Crystal habit">habit</a>, but this statement actually refer=
s to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhombic_dodecahedron" tit=
le=3D"Rhombic dodecahedron">rhombic dodecahedron</a> shape.<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-wn_40-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R=
egular_dodecahedron#cite_note-wn-40"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
0<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Various models have been proposed for the global geometry of the uni=
verse. These proposals include the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Homology_sphere#Cosmology" title=3D"Homology sphere">Poincar=C3=A9 dodecah=
edral space</a>, a positively curved space consisting of a regular dodecahe=
dron whose opposite faces correspond (with a small twist). This was propose=
d by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean-Pierre_Luminet" title=3D=
"Jean-Pierre Luminet">Jean-Pierre Luminet</a> and colleagues in 2003,<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-luminet_41-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-luminet-41"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and an=
 optimal orientation on the sky for the model was estimated in 2008.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-rbsg_42-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-rbsg-42"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
