1d/Jogo_icosiano_01.jpg/250px-Jogo_icosiano_01.jpg" decoding=3D"async" widt=
h=3D"148" height=3D"104" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"600" =
data-file-height=3D"420"></a></span></div></div></div><div class=3D"trow" s=
tyle=3D"display:flex"><div class=3D"thumbcaption">The dodecahedral graph's =
Hamiltonian property and the mathematical toy <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Icosian_game" title=3D"Icosian game">Icosian game</a></div></di=
v></div></div>
<p>According to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steinitz%27s_theor=
em" title=3D"Steinitz's theorem">Steinitz's theorem</a>, the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_(discrete_mathematics)" title=3D"Graph (di=
screte mathematics)">graph</a> can be represented as the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skeleton_(topology)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Skeleton (topology)">skeleton</a> of a polyhedron; roughly speaking, a fram=
ework of a polyhedron. Such a graph has two properties. It is <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Planar_graph" title=3D"Planar graph">planar</a>=
, meaning the edges of a graph are connected to every vertex without crossi=
ng other edges. It is also <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K-verte=
x-connected_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"K-vertex-connected graph"=
>three-connected graph</a>: whenever a graph with more than three vertices =
and two of its vertices removed, the edges remain connected.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-grunbaum-2003_43-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-grunbaum-2003-43"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-ziegler_44-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-ziegler-44"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The =
skeleton of a regular dodecahedron can be represented as a graph, and it is=
 called the <b>dodecahedral graph</b>, a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Platonic_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Platonic graph">Plato=
nic graph</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-rudolph_45-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-rudolph-45=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup>
</p><p>This graph can also be constructed as the <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Generalized_Petersen_graph" title=3D"Generalized Petersen gr=
aph">generalized Petersen graph</a> <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-mat=
h-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11=
y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Math=
ML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle G(10,2)}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>G</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mn>10</mn>
        <mo>,</mo>
        <mn>2</mn>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle G(10,2)}</ann=
otation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/70f978207d9fd0e32515f4136d9c9a4bf70975e9" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:8.157ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle G(1=
0,2)}"></span>, where the vertices of a decagon are connected to those of t=
wo pentagons, one pentagon connected to odd vertices of the decagon and the=
 other pentagon connected to the even vertices.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-ps_46-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodec=
ahedron#cite_note-ps-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>46<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Geometrically, this can be visualized =
as the ten-vertex equatorial belt of the dodecahedron connected to the two =
5-vertex polar regions, one on each side.
</p><p>The high degree of symmetry of the polygon is replicated in the prop=
erties of this graph, which are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Di=
stance-transitive_graph" title=3D"Distance-transitive graph">distance-trans=
itive</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-gr_47-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-gr-47"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Distance-regular_graph" title=3D"=
Distance-regular graph">distance-regular</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric_graph" title=3D"Symmetric graph">symmetric</a>. T=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_automorphism" title=3D"Gr=
aph automorphism">automorphism group</a> has order a hundred and twenty. Th=
e vertices can be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_coloring" =
title=3D"Graph coloring">colored</a> with 3 colors, as can the edges, and t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_diameter" class=3D"mw-red=
irect" title=3D"Graph diameter">diameter</a> is five.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dode=
cahedron#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>48<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The dodecahedral graph is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/H=
amiltonian_graph" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hamiltonian graph">Hamilto=
nian</a>, meaning a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Path_(graph_th=
eory)" title=3D"Path (graph theory)">path</a> visits all of its vertices ex=
actly once. The name of this property is named after <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Rowan_Hamilton" title=3D"William Rowan Hamilton"=
>William Rowan Hamilton</a>, who invented a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Mathematical_game" title=3D"Mathematical game">mathematical game<=
/a> known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Icosian_game" tit=
le=3D"Icosian game">icosian game</a>. The game's object was to find a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamiltonian_cycle" class=3D"mw-redirect=
" title=3D"Hamiltonian cycle">Hamiltonian cycle</a> along the edges of a do=
decahedron.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-bondy-murty_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_dodecahedron#cite_note-bondy-mur=
ty-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p>
